he construction of a “post-natural” world. Using a combination of personal memoirs and formal essays, Every Grain of Sand seeks to involve readers in the extraordinary places they inhabit—and usually take for granted—and will appeal to both the general reader and to students in humanities, social sciences, and environmental studies. It is unique for its presentation of entirely Canadian perspectives on ecology and environmental issues.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnvironmental degradation. 0aHuman ecologyzCanada. 0aHuman ecology. 0aNaturexEffect of human beings on. 4aEnvironmental Studies. 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Essays.2bisacsh1 aArmitage, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyanowsky, Ehor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalton, Anne Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlazebrook, Trish, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHummel, Monte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJalava, Jarmo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrug, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMay, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMortimer-Sandilands, Catriona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOerlemans, Onno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRubinoff, Lionel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimpson, Leanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWainwright, J.A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWainwright, J.A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.go